  "run_idx": 1,
  "status": "complete_with_errors",
  "started_at": "2026-05-27T22:16:48.294751",
  "completed_at": "2026-05-27T23:20:30.499051",
  "random_seed": 2511189227,
  "free_responses": {
    "M1": "## Recommendation: Option A (Predicted short-term survival via SOFA)\n\nAdopt SOFA-based short-term survival prediction as the formal protocol. Under sustained overflow with eight net admissions per day, the protocol's first job is to prevent the worst outcome of crisis medicine: people dying in hallways while ICU beds hold patients who will not survive regardless. SOFA does this directly. It uses a metric clinicians already calculate, applies to the actual clinical question being asked (will this patient survive this admission?), and limits the scope of moral judgment to something physicians are trained and licensed to assess. Courts have repeatedly upheld it. Families can be told the truth: \"We are giving the bed to the patient most likely to walk out of it.\" That sentence is communicable at 2 a.m. to an exhausted charge nurse and to a grieving spouse.\n\nThe most compelling alternative is Option E — categorical exclusion plus lottery. Its egalitarian appeal is real, and it spares staff the agony of ranking. But a lottery during a six-week overflow with a known mortality gradient means knowingly trading survivors for non-survivors in significant numbers. That is not humility before moral complexity; it is a refusal to use information we have. Option B's QALY weighting collapses under disability-rights law and public legitimacy. Option D's instrumental and behavioral criteria will not survive first contact with a journalist. Option C sounds fair but in practice rewards proximity to ambulances and well-resourced referral networks.\n\nThe case that would make me regret this: a 45-year-old with long-standing cystic fibrosis, baseline organ dysfunction inflating her SOFA, denied a bed that goes to a previously healthy 70-year-old with better acute physiology. She dies. Her chronic illness, not her acute prognosis, effectively decided it. That is a real harm and I will not pretend otherwise. I would still defend the choice because the alternative protocols would not have saved her either — lottery would have given her a coin flip, QALY scoring would have weighed against her, FCFS would have depended on her ambulance route — and across hundreds of decisions, SOFA produces the fewest preventable deaths with the least discretionary bias. We owe her honesty about the tradeoff, mitigation through disability-adjusted SOFA review, and a public commitment to end crisis standards the moment capacity allows.",
    "M2": "Adopt **Option A: Predicted short-term survival**.\n\nIn sustained ICU overflow, the system’s first ethical duty is to use scarce critical-care capacity where it is most likely to prevent imminent death. A protocol based on SOFA and expected 28-day survival is clinically intelligible, operational within a week, legally more defensible than quality-of-life or age-weighted approaches, and clear enough to explain to families: ICU beds are prioritized for patients most likely to survive the acute episode with ICU care. It also replaces hidden bedside rationing with a uniform rule applied across all five hospitals.\n\nThe most compelling alternative is first-come-first-served. It feels fair because it avoids ranking lives and reduces physician discretion. But under sustained overflow, it is not truly neutral. It rewards timing, geography, transfer access, and advocacy. It also allows scarce ICU beds to remain occupied by patients with very low likelihood of survival while patients with much better near-term prospects die waiting. That is a procedural fairness that produces avoidable deaths and disguises rationing rather than governing it.\n\nThe case that would make me most regret this choice is a patient with chronic organ dysfunction or disability whose SOFA score looks poor at baseline but who, in ordinary conditions, might survive with ICU care; under this protocol, that patient could lose priority to someone with a cleaner baseline and only modestly better short-term prognosis. That is the moral danger of Option A, and it demands strict implementation discipline: decisions must be based on individualized near-term survival, not disability, age, social worth, or predicted quality of life.\n\nI would still defend the choice because the alternatives either embed less acceptable judgments—QALYs, life-cycle preferences, instrumental value, blame for risk-taking—or abandon the duty to save the most lives possible. Option A is painful, but in this circumstance it is the clearest, most clinically grounded, and most accountable protocol.",
    "M3": "I strongly recommend adopting **Option A (Predicted short-term survival)**. Faced with a sustained, insurmountable capacity deficit, our paramount ethical mandate must be to maximize the absolute number of lives saved. Option A achieves this by relying on objective, well-established clinical metrics (SOFA scores). Because SOFA is natively understood by our exhausted ICU staff, this protocol can actually be operationalized and effectively communicated within the strict seven-day deadline. Furthermore, it explicitly replaces ad-hoc, informal biases with a legally tested framework, grounding agonizing triage and withdrawal decisions in clinical realities rather than individual physician discretion.\n\nThe most compelling alternative is Option E (Categorical exclusion + lottery). Option E’s strict egalitarianism is highly attractive because it shields staff from the moral injury of ranking human lives and neatly circumvents the structural biases against chronic illness inherent in organ failure scoring. However, we must reject it. Emergency triage requires ruthless resource stewardship; submitting scarce, life-saving beds to random chance abandons our clinical expertise. Arbitrarily prioritizing a patient with a 15% survival probability over one with an 85% probability—simply because both cleared a minimum exclusion threshold—is an abdication of medical duty that would result in vastly more preventable deaths across our 4M population.\n\nThe specific case that will make me deeply regret this choice is a young adult with a severe, chronic disability who contracts the virus. Because their baseline SOFA score is inherently compromised by their underlying condition, they could be denied admission—or actively withdrawn from a bed—in favor of a previously healthy, older patient who has acute failure but a superior statistical chance of rapid rebound. \n\nI will nonetheless defend Option A because a sustained daily deficit of eight patients means that profound tragedy is mathematically unavoidable. If we abandon survival-based triage to protect those marginalized by clinical scoring, we will inevitably kill more patients in the aggregate through random allocation, or we will gridlock our emergency departments until people simply die in the waiting rooms. Under scarcity, there are no bloodless choices; Option A demands we confront that reality and minimize the total death toll.",
    "M4": "I recommend **Option C: First-come-first-served with medical floor** as the adopted protocol. This is not a retreat from clinical reasoning but a deliberate, defensible scaffold that replaces ad-hoc, hidden bias with a transparent, operationalizable rule. In a sustained crisis with exhausted staff, the primary ethical imperative is to restore consistency and trust. Option C does this by defining clear ICU-need criteria and then allocating beds solely on arrival time—no withdrawal except for medical futility. It eliminates the moral injury of clinicians playing gatekeeper with scoring systems, and it is the most legally robust path: courts routinely uphold queue-based allocation when capacity is overwhelmed, because it treats every patient as an equal, sovereign claimant.\n\nThe most compelling alternative is Option A, which promises to maximize lives saved via predictive scoring. But that protocol is ethically fragile in practice. It requires continuous recalculation and withdrawal of care—an act that, in the absence of consent, is indistinguishable from euthanasia for families and staff alike, and it silently discriminates against patients with high baseline SOFA due to chronic disease, the very populations already suffering disproportionate harm. Our exhausted clinicians would bear the full psychological weight of ranking and removing patients, eroding their resilience precisely when we need it most. Predictive scores may seem objective, but they embed structural injustice; a first-come queue, by contrast, refuses to encode such judgments.\n\nThe patient case that would test my resolve: a 50-year-old acute respiratory distress patient, previously fit, arrives just after the last bed is claimed by an 80-year-old with multiple comorbidities. The younger patient dies in the emergency department hours later. I feel the pull to rescue the one with higher predicted survival. But I defend the protocol because without it, we would still be making that terrible choice—only through gut instinct, personal bias, or pressure from privileged families, which is precisely the informal triage we seek to end. The queue does not promise to save every salvageable life; it promises that no life is deemed less worthy because of a score. That commitment preserves the social trust that holds our health system together, and in a pandemic, trust is a non-negotiable clinical resource.",
    "M5": " **Recommendation: Adopt Option A: Predicted short-term survival**\n\nWith ICU occupancy fixed at 95 percent and a net daily accumulation of eight critically ill patients, this health system is no longer managing a temporary surge but a sustained physiological catastrophe. In this environment, a triage protocol must do more than allocate incoming admissions; it must create lawful, explicit turnover among current patients when critical care becomes futile. Option A is the only candidate that operationalizes this brute physical reality. By using the SOFA score and predicted 28-day survival as universal, objectively applied thresholds, it replaces the unofficial, inconsistent rationing already occurring with a transparent standard that physicians already know and can calculate under duress. Courts have upheld similar frameworks because prognostic criteria are clinically grounded rather than based on identity, age, or social worth. The communication burden is also manageable: priority goes to those most likely to survive the acute event, full stop.\n\nThe strongest objection comes from procedural fairness advocates, particularly the appeal of Option C. A first-come-first-served queue feels morally gentler because it spares staff from actively ranking lives and avoids withdrawal decisions. But in sustained overflow, a queue without an evidence-based liberation mechanism does not prevent death; it merely displaces it to emergency departments, ambulances, and medical wards while finite ventilators and dialysis machines remain tethered to patients with negligible chance of recovery. Fair process cannot outweigh the duty to steward scarce, life-sustaining resources toward survival.\n\nThe case that would haunt me is a young patient with severe but chronic baseline organ dysfunction—say, advanced sickle cell disease or cystic fibrosis—whose elevated SOFA score systematically pessimizes a genuine chance of meaningful recovery, leading to denial or compassionate withdrawal. It is a tragic, discriminatory outcome for an",
    "M6": "**Recommendation: Adopt Option A (Predicted short-term survival via SOFA score)**\n\nIn a crisis of sustained ICU overflow, the primary moral and operational imperative must be to save the most lives possible with the limited resources available. Option A—prioritizing patients based on predicted short-term survival using the SOFA score—best meets this goal while offering the clarity, defensibility, and speed required for implementation. The SOFA score is a validated, objective tool already familiar to clinicians, reducing cognitive burden on exhausted staff and minimizing arbitrary decision-making. Courts have upheld similar protocols, and its focus on immediate survival aligns with the acute nature of the crisis, avoiding the ethical and legal pitfalls of long-term outcome predictions or implicit age discrimination.\n\nThe most compelling alternative, Option C (first-come-first-served), appeals to procedural fairness but fails the core test of a triage protocol: it does not optimize outcomes. While it avoids the discomfort of \"ranking lives,\" it passively accepts preventable deaths by ignoring clinically meaningful differences in survival probability. In a pandemic where every bed counts, this is a luxury we cannot afford. Option A’s withdrawal-of-care provision, though morally difficult, is necessary to ensure beds are used for patients with the highest likelihood of recovery. Staff moral injury is a real concern, but it is mitigated by the protocol’s objectivity and the shared understanding that these decisions are driven by scarcity, not value judgments about individual lives.\n\nThe case that would most test this choice is a young patient with a chronic condition (e.g., cystic fibrosis) who has a lower baseline SOFA score but a strong will to live and a supportive family. Under Option A, they might be deprioritized in favor of an older patient with a higher predicted survival. This is painful, but the alternative—abandoning objective criteria—risks even greater harm through ad hoc decisions or queue-jumping by the well-connected. The SOFA score’s focus on organ failure, not underlying conditions, ensures that discrimination is incidental, not systemic. If we regret this choice, it will be because we failed to expand capacity sooner—but in the moment, Option A is the least bad path forward.\n\nDefensibility hinges on transparency and consistency. Option A provides both, while its alternatives either sacrifice lives (C, E) or introduce unacceptable biases (B, D). In a crisis, we must act decisively to save as many as we can, even when every choice is imperfect.",
    "M7": "The regional health system should adopt **Option A: Predicted short-term survival**. This protocol is the most ethically defensible and operationally feasible choice in the context of a sustained ICU capacity crisis. By prioritizing patients with the highest predicted 28-day survival based on SOFA scores, it directly addresses the immediate goal of maximizing lives saved during the crisis. This approach aligns with the Hippocratic principle of doing the most good for the most people and leverages a scoring system already familiar to clinicians, ensuring rapid implementation within the required 7-day timeframe.\n\nWhile **Option A** may disadvantage patients with chronic conditions, this is a tragic but inevitable consequence of extreme resource scarcity. Courts have upheld similar protocols, recognizing the necessity of prioritizing immediate survival during crises. The risk of staff moral injury from withdrawal decisions is real, but this burden is mitigated by the protocol’s clarity and its focus on objective, widely accepted criteria. Without such a structured approach, staff face even greater distress from ad hoc, inconsistent triage, which erodes trust and fairness.\n\nThe most compelling alternative, **Option B**, fails due to its implicit age bias and culturally charged quality-of-life weighting, which would provoke public backlash and legal challenges. **Option A** avoids these pitfalls by focusing solely on short-term survival, a criterion less vulnerable to accusations of discrimination.\n\nA case that might prompt regret is a younger patient with a chronic condition whose lower baseline SOFA score reduces their priority, even if they have a strong long-term prognosis. However, in a crisis where daily admissions outpace discharges by 8 patients, the system cannot afford to prioritize long-term potential over immediate survival. The protocol’s consistency and transparency ensure that every decision is made on the same objective basis, which remains justifiable even in regrettable cases. \n\nIn adopting **Option A**, the health system prioritizes maximizing lives saved, operational feasibility, and legal defensibility—all critical factors in a sustained capacity overflow. While imperfect, it is the most ethically and practically sound choice available.",
    "M8": "I recommend adopting Option A (Predicted short-term survival). In a sustained, six-week overflow where daily admissions consistently exceed discharges, the primary ethical imperative shifts from individual care to maximizing the total number of lives saved. Option A achieves this by relying on the SOFA score, an objective, familiar, and clinically validated metric. It provides clear, defensible criteria that protect clinicians from the moral injury of ad-hoc decision-making and offers strong legal protection, as courts have consistently upheld short-term survival models in crisis standards of care.\n\nThe most compelling alternative is Option C (First-come-first-served), which appeals to our intuitive sense of procedural fairness. However, in a prolonged overflow, FCFS is operationally fatal. Without a mechanism to prioritize patients based on survivability or to reassess ongoing care, the emergency department queue will grow indefinitely. FCFS effectively rations by waiting time rather than medical need, resulting in higher aggregate mortality and the squandering of scarce ICU resources on patients who may not survive even with intensive care.\n\nThe specific case that would make me regret choosing Option A is a young adult with a severe baseline physical disability, such as cerebral palsy, whose chronically elevated SOFA score deprioritizes them in favor of a previously healthy, older patient with a lower acute score. Denying the younger patient a bed based on a metric that conflates chronic disability with acute mortality risk is deeply distressing. Nevertheless, I would still defend this protocol. In a true crisis, introducing subjective, case-by-case adjustments to compensate for baseline health disparities destroys the protocol’s objectivity, invites bias, and guarantees legal challenges. To save the maximum number of lives, we must rely on strict, uniform clinical metrics, accepting the tragic imperfections of population-level triage over the catastrophic collapse of the entire system.",
    "M9": "## Recommendation: Adopting Option C: First-come-first-served with medical floor\n\nThe most suitable triage protocol for the regional health system under sustained ICU capacity overflow is **Option C: First-come-first-served with medical floor**. This protocol offers a straightforward, fair, and transparent method for allocating the limited ICU beds. By admitting patients in the order they arrive and not withdrawing care except in cases of medical futility, it maintains procedural fairness and minimizes discretion, thereby reducing the potential for bias. \n\nThe primary strength of Option C lies in its simplicity and defensibility. It is easily communicable to both staff and families, as it follows a clear and understandable principle. Moreover, its non-discriminatory nature based on age, quality of life, or other personal characteristics makes it ethically robust and less likely to be challenged in courts or ethics boards.\n\nWhile predictive protocols like **Option A** might maximize immediate survival rates, they risk discriminating against patients with chronic conditions and create moral dilemmas for staff regarding withdrawal of care. **Option C** avoids these issues, preserving staff morale and trust within the community.\n\nA case that might make me regret this choice is that of a young patient with a high likelihood of recovery being admitted after an older patient with a poorer prognosis. However, I would still defend **Option C** because it upholds a principle of fairness that is crucial during a crisis. It ensures that decisions are made based on a clear, non-discriminatory rule, maintaining public trust in the healthcare system.\n\nIn contrast to more complex protocols like **Option D**, which tries to balance multiple values but risks being too complicated and potentially biased, **Option C** offers a clean and uncomplicated approach to triage. Its straightforwardness is key to operationalizing it within the required 7-day timeframe.\n\nTherefore, despite potential drawbacks in terms of aggregate survival rates compared to predictive models, **Option C** is the most appropriate protocol due to its fairness, simplicity, and ethical robustness.",
    "M10": "**Recommended Protocol: Option C – First-come-first-served with medical floor**\n\nThe regional health system should immediately adopt Option C as its formal ICU triage protocol. In a sustained overflow already lasting six weeks, with exhausted staff performing ad-hoc bedside rationing, the highest ethical and operational priority is to replace opaque, emotionally corrosive discretion with a clear, consistent, and procedurally fair rule. Option C achieves this by defining objective minimum medical criteria for ICU admission and then allocating scarce beds strictly by time of arrival, while prohibiting discretionary withdrawal except under ordinary medical futility standards.\n\nThis approach is defensible to courts because it avoids explicit discrimination on the basis of disability, age, perceived social worth, or predicted quality of life. It is communicable to staff and families because the rule is simple: if you meet the medical threshold, you join the queue; once admitted, you are not removed to make room for someone judged “more deserving.” That clarity reduces moral injury among clinicians who are already at breaking point. It also preserves public trust at a moment when confidence in healthcare institutions is fragile; families can be told the system is not secretly ranking lives, even if it cannot save everyone.\n\nWhile predictive models such as Option A would likely produce higher aggregate short-term survival, the price is too high. Asking frontline teams to repeatedly withdraw life-sustaining treatment from existing patients because a new arrival has a better SOFA score would intensify moral distress, invite litigation on disability-discrimination grounds, and be nearly impossible to explain transparently at the bedside. Option C accepts a measurable reduction in lives saved as the necessary cost of preserving the moral integrity of the clinical relationship and the legitimacy of the institution.\n\nI would most regret this choice in the case of a 32-year-old previously healthy mother of two with rapidly progressive viral pneumonia who arrives moments after a frail 78-year-old with advanced comorbidities and poorer prognosis. Under Option C she might die while the older patient occupies the last bed. That outcome would be tragic. Nevertheless, I would defend the protocol because the alternative—explicitly telling the younger patient’s family that we are removing or denying care because we have calculated her life as statistically less valuable—erodes the foundational medical norm that we do not sacrifice identifiable patients for statistical gain. Once that line is crossed under crisis conditions, it is difficult to re-establish. In sustained catastrophe, procedural justice and the refusal to instrumentalize individual lives remain the least-bad foundations for triage. Option C provides them."
  },
